items.title: NT students required to sing national anthem
items.standfirst: O fficials say singing Advance Australia Fair at assemblies and school events will restore "national pride".
items.content: P ublic school students in the Northern Territory will sing the national anthem at assemblies and special events under a new directive from the Top End government.The mandatory measure introduced today is about "restoring national pride" in public schools, the NT government says.Schools will be required to play and sing both verses of Advance Australia Fair in English during assemblies and special events.READ MORE: Israeli President to meet Albanese, Bondi victims on visit to Australia Students who can will be expected to stand while the anthem is played. Education Minister Jo Hersey said students had "been deprived of feeling proud to be Australian" and the new measure would bring back national pride."We are Australian, and in the Northern Territory students will be taught what it means to be an Australian and to be proud of their country," she said.She said Welcome to Country practices would remain the same and at the discretion of individual schools.The NT government is also updating the school curriculum for students to learn about national symbols and what they mean to Australian identity through the civics and citizenship learning area.In January 2021, the second line of the anthem was changed from "For we are young and free" to "For we are one and free", in acknowledgement of Indigenous Australians.NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here

clusters.title: Australian dollar cracks 70 US cents on climb to three-year high
clusters.neutral_headline: Australian dollar cracks 70 US cents on climb to three-year high

items.title: Australian dollar cracks 70 US cents on climb to three-year high
items.standfirst: T he local currency today was worth US70 cents, its highest since February 2023.
items.content: The Australian dollar has surged overnight to its highest level against its US counterpart since February 2023, driven by a plunge in the greenback.The Aussie currency was buying US70.11 cents earlier today after climbing 1.4 per cent.It hit the mark in the lead-up to the release of new inflation figures today, expected at 11.30am.READ MORE: The silver lining for the Australian dollar The Reserve Bank of Australia is tipped to lift interest rates at its meeting next week if there is a larger-than-expected increase in consumer prices.IG market analyst Tony Sycamore told the Australian Financial Review that geopolitical uncertainty and a falling greenback were behind the spike in the Aussie dollar."The Australian dollar's gains continued to be driven by a number of factors, including broad-based weakness in the US dollar which has accelerated post last weeks Greenland drama's and is now poised for a perilous break lower," he said.On Tuesday (US Eastern Time) the US dollar recorded its lowest one-day drop since last April after US President Donald Trump said he was not concerned about its recent falls, reports Reuters."I think it's great," he said, when asked if the US dollar's value had declined too much."The dollar's doing great."It finished Tuesday at a four-year low. clusters.neutral_headline: Warning over dangers of 'back to school' photos

items.title: Warning over dangers of 'back to school' photos
items.standfirst: Federal police said it was "important to be mindful".
items.content: Federal police have issued a warning over "back to school" photos as parents and kids mark the start of the school year.Back-to-school pictures are of course traditional and a long-standing favourite for proud families to share on social media.However, in a social media post, the AFP said it was "important to be mindful" about what was posted online, as some details could potentially identify a child.READ MORE: Apple Watch can now detect major stroke, heart attack factor "These identifiable details can be anything from logos to school signs, featured anywhere from uniforms to image backgrounds," the AFP said.If parents can't obscure these details from the camera, they should take the pictures on their smartphone and edit them.While the process and options differ slightly between iPhone and Android , people can use various editing tools, emojis, and even AI, to ensure their child's privacy is protected before posting.READ MORE: Pauline Hanson leaps ahead of Sussan Ley as preferred prime minister The AFP posted instructional videos for both iPhone and Android users online. Outside of keeping the photo innocuous, parents and carers can also take extra steps for safety when posting it.They are advised to check their social media privacy settings and make sure social media accounts are secure.READ MORE: US sending ICE unit to Winter Olympics for security Also, a child's personal information, including their full name and age, should be kept private.These steps are especially important in the new world of AI and deepfakes."A little caution can help keep kids safe online," the AFP's post concluded.NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here

clusters.title: US sending ICE unit to Winter Olympics for security
clusters.neutral_headline: US sending ICE unit to Winter Olympics for security

items.title: US sending ICE unit to Winter Olympics for security
items.standfirst: Olympics h ost nation Italy has expressed concern the controversial US federal agents will be deployed during the Games.
items.content: News that a unit of US Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) would be present during the upcoming Winter Games has set off concern and confusion in Italy, where people have expressed outrage at the inclusion of an agency that has dominated headlines for leading the Trump administration's immigration crackdown.Homeland Security Investigations (HSI), a unit within ICE that focuses on cross-border crimes, frequently sends its officers to overseas events such as the Olympics to help with security.HSI officers are separate from the ICE arm at the forefront of the immigration crackdown known as Enforcement and Removal Operations, and there was no indication ERO officers were being sent to Italy.READ MORE: Man reported critical in shooting involving US Border Patrol Italy reacts to US security deploymentThe reaction among some in Italy reflects not only a worsening perception abroad of the administration's tactics on immigration but also underscores a broader rift between the US under President Donald Trump and its international allies.Vague reports that ICE would be deployed in some capacity surfaced over the weekend, resulting in a series of online petitions gathering support of people opposed to the presence of ICE at the Games. They followed a RAI news report that aired Sunday showing an Italian news crew being threatened in Minneapolis by ICE agents.Trump's immigration crackdown has in recent weeks intensified in Minneapolis, leading to the fatal shootings of two US citizens at the hands of federal immigration officers.Milan Mayor Giuseppe Sala said that ICE would not be welcome in his city, which is hosting the February 6 opening ceremony to be attended by US Vice President JD Vance, as well as most ice sports."This is a militia that kills, a militia that enters into the homes of people, signing their own permission slips. It is clear they are not welcome in Milan, without a doubt," Sala told RTL Radio 102.READ MORE: Pauline Hanson leaps ahead of Sussan Ley as preferred prime ministerItaly's Interior Ministry said later that the HSI investigators would be stationed at a control room at the US consulate in Milan, in a support role with other American law enforcement agencies, and that they would not include personnel involved in immigration controls in the US.It noted in a statement issued after Interior Minister Matteo Piantedosi and US Ambassador Tilman Fertitta met on Tuesday that HSI agents are present in more than 50 countries, including for many years Italy."All of the security operations in the territory remain as always the exclusive responsibility and direction of Italian authorities,'' the ministry said.Working behind the scenes The ICE agents deployed to Italy for the Games will have a different role from the one seen in immigration crackdowns in the US, officials have stressed."Obviously, ICE does not conduct immigration enforcement operations in foreign countries,″ the Department of Homeland Security said in a statement."At the Olympics, ICE's Homeland Security Investigations is supporting the U.S. Department of State's Diplomatic Security Service and host nation to vet and mitigate risks from transnational criminal organisations. All security operations remain under Italian authority."A US official speaking on condition of anonymity to discuss security measures said the general public likely wouldn't even see or be aware of the HSI agents on the ground during the Olympics.The official said HSI agents would be working behind the scenes, mainly in offices or the US consulate in Milan, as they have done during previous international events.NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here
